research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0005.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"factorized_topk likely failed because its hidden mixer is too narrow and lossy; widening that stage and adding a gate should preserve more information before latent selection and materially improve FVU. Re-test factorized_topk at K=128 after this single architectural stabilization edit.","summary":"The first factorized_topk prototype was much worse than the anchor, but its implementation used a plain hidden layer with width equal to d_in, which is a likely bottleneck rather than a decisive family verdict. This round keeps the same family and K while upgrading the encoder to a wider gated mixer.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a coherent follow-up on the only family that produced a strongly different signal, and it targets an obvious implementation bottleneck instead of abandoning the branch too early. The edit increases encoder compute, so even a quality gain still needs later cost scrutiny.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/factorized_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["The original factorized_topk prototype likely suffered from an overly narrow d_in-sized hidden bottleneck rather than only a bad family prior.","Round 5 stabilizes factorized_topk by replacing the narrow ReLU mixer with a wider gated hidden stage before latent projection."],"next_hypotheses":["If the stabilized factorized_topk proxy improves substantially, consider promotion or a follow-up quality pass with optimizer tuning.","If the stabilized factorized_topk remains poor under normal runtime, deprioritize the current built-in families and move to a genuinely new encoder family rather than more local tuning."]}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0063.json:22:    "expected_win": "lower_cost",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk has now beaten the K=128 full baseline, so the next quality-first move is to stabilize the same family with an optimizer better suited to its smooth nonlinear residual branch. Test hybrid_topk at K=128 with Adam to see whether denser adaptive updates improve FVU beyond the current full frontier.","summary":"hybrid_topk is the first family to improve the K=128 full frontier, but the gain is still small relative to the aggressive quality target. This round keeps the architecture fixed and changes only the optimizer to probe whether the family is currently undertrained rather than intrinsically capped.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a disciplined follow-up because the family finally showed real full-run promise and deserves one quality-focused stabilization pass before opening more architectures. Adam may not help, but it tests a concrete training-dynamics hypothesis without confounding the model design.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk is now the best full K=128 frontier at FVU 0.18129383772611618, narrowly beating the previous topk anchor 0.18532327562570572.","Round 8 keeps focus on hybrid_topk and tests whether Adam can better optimize its nonlinear residual branch than signum."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk plus Adam improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the new mainline family candidate.","If hybrid_topk plus Adam is flat or worse, keep the family but try a higher-capacity quality pass such as larger expansion_factor before considering cost reduction or lower K."]}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0001.json:22:    "expected_win": "lower_cost",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0007.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A hybrid encoder that preserves the strong linear topk path and adds a gated nonlinear residual to latent logits can improve quality without discarding the baseline behavior that already works. Test a new hybrid_topk family at K=128 as a quality-first architecture probe.","summary":"factorized_topk improved from its worst prototype but is still far from the K=128 anchor, and the current built-in families are not showing a path to the target. This round opens a new family designed to be safer than pure nonlinear encoders by keeping the baseline linear path intact and only learning a nonlinear correction on top.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a broader architecture move, but it is still a single coherent bet: combine the proven linear encoder with a nonlinear residual branch instead of replacing it. The new family adds compute, so even a promising quality signal would need later cost validation.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/hybrid_topk_sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/__init__.py"],"notes_to_memory":["The fixed factorized_topk stabilization improved proxy FVU from 0.4431915953755379 to 0.3485000617802143 without runtime regression, but it remains far from the K=128 topk anchor.","Round 7 opens hybrid_topk, a new family that keeps the baseline linear topk encoder and adds a gated nonlinear residual to latent logits rather than replacing the linear path outright."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk shows a clear proxy gain, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or nonlinear branch width before promotion.","If hybrid_topk is also flat or worse, pause family proliferation and reconsider whether quality gains are more likely to come from topk-mainline training dynamics than from encoder architecture alone."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0019.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The round-18 refined_topk crash was caused by a mixed-precision implementation bug in the ridge solve, not by evidence against the architecture. Running the small support-wise solve in float32 and casting the refined coefficients back to the model dtype should make the family trainable under bf16 autocast, allowing a valid proxy read on whether coefficient refitting can lower FVU at K=128.","summary":"Keep refined_topk alive for one crash-recovery follow-up. The architecture stays the same, but its coefficient-refinement solve is now executed in a stable float32 path so the proxy run can test the actual quality hypothesis instead of failing on dtype mismatch.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a narrow implementation-fix round on the most recent crashing family, which is the right move after a first-run failure with a clear stack trace. The main risk is that the architecture may still be weak even after the fix, but a clean rerun is more informative than abandoning the family based on a bf16/autocast bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 fixes a refined_topk mixed-precision bug: the support-wise ridge solve now runs in float32 and casts refined coefficients back to the model dtype.","The refined_topk crash in round 18 came from a bf16/float32 mismatch inside torch.linalg.solve under autocast, so that round should not be treated as architecture evidence.","A local bf16 import/forward/backward sanity check passed for the fixed refined_topk implementation before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If the fixed refined_topk yields a meaningful proxy FVU gain, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on regularization strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk now runs normally but lands near the recent 0.275 proxy plateau, conclude that coefficient refitting alone is insufficient and pivot to a genuinely different encoder family next round."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated factorized_topk SAE with a narrow nonlinear hidden mixing stage will beat the current rotated linear top-k proxy anchor on FVU by giving the encoder more expressive support selection than a single linear projection, without changing the fixed-K decode path.","summary":"Add a new factorized_topk prototype under sparsify/ and run it as a proxy at K=128 with Hadamard and the baseline signum optimizer. This is a quality-first architecture exploration step after the residual_topk stabilization regression, so the next move is a different higher-expressivity encoder family rather than another weak local sweep.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows research/program.md: one coherent hypothesis, proxy by default, and architecture exploration after a normal-health residual_topk follow-up regressed. The implementation stays entirely under sparsify/, preserves the fixed execution layer, and passed a local instantiation plus forward/backward sanity check. The main risk is that the added nonlinearity may make optimization harder under signum, so a weak first proxy would argue for either optimizer-specific stabilization or abandoning this family quickly.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py","sparsify/__init__.py","sparsify/factorized_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; after the residual_topk stabilization pass regressed under normal runtime, the right next move is a new quality-first architecture family rather than more narrow local tuning.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Added a factorized_topk prototype that inserts a narrow nonlinear hidden projection before latent scoring, keeping the standard decoder and fixed-K top-k interface intact.","Local sanity check passed for factorized_topk: Python instantiation plus forward/backward succeeded on a toy tensor, so the family is compatible with the existing SparseCoder training path."],"next_hypotheses":["If factorized_topk shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization pass over optimizer or orthogonality regularization before considering any smaller-K search.","If factorized_topk improves quality but shows a runtime regression, follow with an edit_perf_code pass on the extra hidden projection path instead of discarding the family.","If factorized_topk is clearly weak on proxy FVU, move on to a different higher-expressivity family such as a wider routed or multi-branch encoder rather than continuing local sweeps."]}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0081.json:22:    "expected_win": "lower_cost",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A soft mixture-of-experts encoder may beat the current K=128 topk anchor by giving the encoder more routing expressivity without the hard-capacity bottlenecks of grouped routing. Test the existing mixture_topk family at the same K=128 and expansion factor as a quality-first proxy comparison.","summary":"The K=128 topk full baseline is now anchored at FVU 0.1853. The next round should probe a more expressive encoder family at the same K rather than shrinking K or spending another round on local topk tuning.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"mixture_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is the right point to open architecture exploration, but it is still a first incubation pass, so the result may be noisy or need follow-up tuning before judging the family. I kept the rest of the setup close to the anchor to preserve interpretability.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"mixture_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Established full K=128 topk anchor is FVU 0.18532327562570572; future lower-K or cost-driven moves should clear that quality bar first.","Round 2 opens the first new architecture family by testing mixture_topk as a quality-first encoder at the same K=128 anchor point."],"next_hypotheses":["If mixture_topk shows even modest proxy FVU gain, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or expansion factor before judging promotion.","If mixture_topk is flat or worse under normal runtime, try another expressive family such as residual_topk or factorized_topk at the same K=128 anchor."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0009.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk with Adam is now the strongest K=128 configuration, so the next quality-first move is to increase representational capacity rather than shrink K or chase cost. Test hybrid_topk at K=128 with Adam and expansion_factor=16 to see whether extra latent capacity can materially reduce FVU again.","summary":"The hybrid_topk Adam stabilization produced a meaningful full improvement to 0.1619 FVU, but that is still far from the aggressive target. This round keeps the best family and optimizer fixed and spends one proxy run on a larger expansion factor as the cleanest quality-first scaling test.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is the right next bet because the current mainline finally has momentum and deserves capacity scaling before any lower-K or cost tradeoffs. The main risk is that extra capacity may give only marginal quality gains relative to added memory and compute.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk plus Adam improved the full K=128 frontier to FVU 0.16189537942409515 with no runtime regression relative to the prior hybrid run.","Round 9 escalates capacity within the leading family by testing expansion_factor=16 at fixed K=128 and Adam before considering any lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk with Adam and expansion_factor=16 improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the new mainline quality candidate.","If the larger expansion factor is flat or only marginally better, keep hybrid_topk as mainline and look for a more targeted architectural improvement rather than scaling capacity further."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0007.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The current residual_topk prototype is likely capped by its fixed half-and-half latent budget: each branch can only nominate roughly K/2 features before the final merge, so the better branch cannot claim more of the final support even when it should. Letting both branches over-propose up to K candidates and then selecting the final global top-K from their union should preserve the residual design while removing this allocation bottleneck, improving FVU at fixed K=128.","summary":"Stabilize the promoted residual_topk family with a narrow architecture edit: remove the fixed per-branch K split so both the base and residual branches can each propose up to K candidates before the final global top-K selection. Run this as a proxy quality-first comparison at K=128 with the existing Hadamard+signum setup to test whether the family had been artificially capacity-limited.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays within one coherent hypothesis and follows the program guidance to keep pushing a promising family before chasing smaller K or cost. I kept the execution layer unchanged, edited only sparsify/, and avoided mixing in optimizer or regularization sweeps so the result isolates the branch-allocation change. The main risk is extra duplicate candidates across branches with no quality gain, but the local forward/backward sanity check passed and runtime cost should remain close enough for a proxy read.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/residual_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding and respected the quality-first objective; with residual_topk newly promoted and still far from the aggressive target, a family-specific stabilization edit is more justified than smaller-K search.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Updated residual_topk so both branches can each propose up to K candidates before the final global top-k, removing the previous fixed half-and-half branch budget that could cap the family.","Local sanity check passed after the edit: residual_topk still instantiates and runs forward/backward successfully on a toy tensor."],"next_hypotheses":["If oversubscribed residual_topk improves proxy FVU, promote to full and then test residual_topk-specific stabilization such as ortho_lambda or Adam without changing K.","If quality improves but throughput regresses, follow with an edit_perf_code pass focused on the residual branch merge path rather than discarding the family.","If this edit does not improve residual_topk meaningfully, move to a different higher-expressivity family such as a factorized or wider multi-branch routed encoder instead of continuing narrow local sweeps."]}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:30:    "expected_win": "explore_unknown",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0004.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A factorized nonlinear encoder may lower FVU at K=128 by adding a hidden mixing stage before latent scoring, giving the encoder more expressive feature composition while keeping the fixed-K decode path unchanged. Test factorized_topk at the same K=128 anchor point as the next quality-first family.","summary":"Both mixture_topk and residual_topk archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU near the topk proxy anchor, so the next move is another architecture family rather than smaller-K search. factorized_topk is the clearest remaining low-friction expressivity upgrade in the current codebase.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is still exploratory, but it continues the right search pattern: hold K fixed, change one architectural idea, and see whether encoder expressivity can move proxy FVU. If this also comes back flat, the current built-in families are not yet showing a path to the target.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["residual_topk at K=128/ef8/signum archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU 0.3055884689092636, so the residual two-branch prototype did not improve on the anchor.","Round 4 opens factorized_topk as the next expressive family to test at fixed K=128 before considering lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If factorized_topk improves proxy FVU, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or expansion factor before promotion.","If factorized_topk is also flat or worse, shift from parameter-only family swapping to a code edit that introduces a genuinely new encoder family or materially changes one incubating family."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0001.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Because the frontier is empty, the next highest-value move is to establish a trustworthy K=128 quality anchor with the simplest mainline architecture before rewarding smaller K or drawing conclusions about new families. Run a proxy topk baseline at K=128 with the default expansion and optimizer explicitly pinned so later rounds can measure real FVU gains against a stable reference.","summary":"No reliable K=128 anchor exists in memory yet. This round should spend one proxy run on an explicitly pinned mainline topk baseline so subsequent architecture work can target material FVU improvement rather than comparing against an implicit or drifting default.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This is intentionally conservative, but the memory is empty and the primary objective depends on having a trustworthy K=128 reference. I avoided architecture edits because there is not yet enough evidence to justify a new family over first establishing the anchor.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 0 starts with empty frontier and no trustworthy K=128 anchor, so anchor establishment takes priority over lower-K comparisons.","Treat this run as the baseline reference point for future aggressive FVU-improvement bets."],"next_hypotheses":["If this anchor is stable, escalate immediately to a higher-capacity or more expressive encoder family that could materially beat its FVU at the same K=128.","If the anchor quality is already much better than expected, then test quality-first upgrades such as mixture/factorized/residual encoders before considering smaller K."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated JumpReLU encoder with a nontrivial learned threshold will suppress weak nuisance activations before top-k selection, improving support precision enough to beat the rotated topk anchor on proxy FVU.","summary":"Run a proxy prototype for a rotated JumpReLU family at K=128. This keeps the quality-first anchor fixed while testing whether thresholded sparse activation can materially outperform rotated topk, instead of spending another round on a likely weak local topk sweep.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"rotated_jumprelu","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This respects the fixed execution layer and uses only env overrides against an already-supported architecture family. It is a single coherent quality-first bet at K=128, which matches the program's guidance to escalate from modest rotated-topk gains into architecture exploration. The main risk is threshold miscalibration: if the initial threshold is too low JumpReLU may collapse toward topk, while if it is too high it may over-prune useful features. Proxy is the right place to test viability before any family-specific stabilization.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.02"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.01"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 2 escalates from modest rotated-topk improvement into a new encoder family rather than continuing local topk tuning.","The current codebase already supports JumpReLU through env overrides, so this prototype can be tested without touching the execution layer.","No operator_hints were present in structured context for this round."],"next_hypotheses":["If rotated JumpReLU shows promising proxy FVU but unstable optimization, keep the family alive with an optimizer-focused stabilization pass such as Adam or LR retuning.","If rotated JumpReLU improves quality but is still far from the aggressive target, sweep its threshold and bandwidth as the next family-specific stabilization step.","If rotated JumpReLU fails to show useful quality signal, move to a different encoder family with stronger routing expressivity rather than returning to weak local topk search."]}
research/history/round_summaries/round_0093.json:22:    "expected_win": "explore_unknown",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0014.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The current best family may need cleaner support suppression rather than another additive or multiplicative residual path. An adaptive-threshold TopK encoder that keeps the proven linear logits as the anchor but learns an input-dependent nonnegative per-latent suppression term could reduce false activations at K=128 and materially improve FVU without abandoning the strong baseline initialization.","summary":"The gated probe was a clear regression, so this round moves to a new architecture edit instead of more parameter-only tuning on weak recent families. The new `adaptive_threshold_topk` family starts exactly from plain TopK behavior and only learns to suppress linear logits, making it a focused quality-first prototype to test at the K=128/ef=8/Adam anchor under proxy.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"adaptive_threshold_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a single coherent architectural bet grounded in the strongest observed prior: keeping the linear TopK path intact. The main risk is that suppression-only flexibility may still be too weak to beat hybrid_topk, but it is safer and more targeted than the recent families that replaced or loosely mixed the baseline encoder.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"adaptive_threshold_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/adaptive_threshold_topk_sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/__init__.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 14 adds a new adaptive_threshold_topk family that preserves the plain linear TopK encoder at initialization and learns only input-dependent nonnegative suppression of latent logits.","A quick local import/forward sanity check passed for adaptive_threshold_topk before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If adaptive_threshold_topk shows a strong proxy gain, promote it to full as the next mainline quality candidate.","If adaptive_threshold_topk is flat or weak, the next round should bias toward a more expressive new architecture or a hybrid-family training-dynamics experiment rather than revisiting gated or jumprelu local sweeps."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0018.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Recent architecture edits have mostly tried to improve support selection, yet multiple distinct families have converged to the same proxy FVU plateau under normal runtime. A stronger next bet is that support is not the main bottleneck at K=128; instead, the selected coefficients are too crude. A refined_topk family that keeps the proven linear top-k support but recomputes the chosen coefficients with a small per-example ridge solve against the decoder atoms could materially lower FVU by directly reducing reconstruction error on the selected support.","summary":"Pivot away from branch-union follow-ups and add a new refined_topk family. It preserves the baseline linear top-k proposal, but replaces the final coefficients with a ridge-refined fit on the chosen decoder features, targeting reconstruction quality directly rather than adding more routing machinery. This is a single proxy prototype for a more radical quality-first hypothesis at the K=128 anchor.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a coherent architecture pivot after two flat union_topk rounds under normal runtime. The main risk is that the per-example solve may add overhead or overfit weak supports, but it tests a meaningfully different failure hypothesis than the recent support-selection families and keeps the launcher interface unchanged.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/__init__.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 18 adds a new refined_topk family that keeps the baseline linear top-k support but refits the selected coefficients with a small ridge solve against the decoder atoms.","The refined_topk implementation uses a straight-through blend so the forward path uses refined coefficients while preserving gradient flow through the baseline top-k activations.","A local import/forward/backward sanity check passed for refined_topk before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If refined_topk materially improves proxy FVU, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on the coefficient refinement strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk is flat or regresses under normal runtime, that is evidence that coefficient refitting alone is not enough and the next round should pivot to a genuinely different encoder family rather than more top-k refinements."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0001.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, enabling Hadamard rotation on the baseline topk SAE will reduce FVU by spreading outlier energy across input dimensions, giving a stronger quality anchor before any lower-K search.","summary":"Run a proxy anchor-refresh experiment that keeps the standard topk SAE at K=128 and turns on Hadamard preprocessing. This is a parameter-only quality-first bet aimed at improving the baseline FVU without conflating the result with smaller K or a new encoder family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"rotated_topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays within the fixed execution layer, makes no code edits, keeps K anchored at 128, and isolates one quality-focused change with plausible upside. The main risk is that Hadamard helps throughput/outlier handling more than reconstruction quality, but it is still the cleanest high-upside baseline refresh available from the current code surface.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 0 chose a quality-first K=128 anchor refresh instead of rewarding smaller K.","The current sparsify code already supports Hadamard-rotated topk SAE through env overrides, so this can be tested without code changes.","No operator_hints were present in structured context for this round."],"next_hypotheses":["If rotated topk materially improves proxy FVU, stabilize that family with optimizer and regularization sweeps before considering smaller K.","If rotated topk does not improve enough, escalate to a new encoder family rather than continuing weak local tuning around vanilla topk.","If rotated topk improves quality but shows poor runtime, follow with a performance-focused pass instead of discarding the direction."]}
