research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:5:{"event_id": "evt_1773953451091356809", "ts": 1773953451, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 4, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "rotated_routed_group_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "rotated_routed_group_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "change_type": "param_only", "expected_win": "lower_fvu", "hypothesis": "At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated routed-group TopK SAE with a differentiable coarse router and Adam optimization will beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU by reducing cross-feature competition before exact latent top-k selection, while avoiding the hard-router failure mode that made plain group_topk unattractive."}}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:13:{"event_id": "evt_1773953554623551045", "ts": 1773953554, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 5, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "rotated_routed_group_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "rotated_routed_group_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "change_type": "edit_sae_code", "expected_win": "explore_unknown", "hypothesis": "The routed_group_topk proxy crash was caused by an optimizer implementation bug, not by the architecture itself: ScheduleFreeWrapperReference writes per-parameter state before delegating to Adam, which makes Adam skip its own state initialization and crash on step 2. If Adam is run without the incompatible wrapper, the same rotated routed_group_topk prototype at K=128 should finally produce a usable quality signal and may beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU."}}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:24:{"event_id": "evt_1773953738657946534", "ts": 1773953738, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 6, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "residual_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "residual_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "change_type": "edit_sae_code", "expected_win": "lower_fvu", "hypothesis": "At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated residual_topk SAE will beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU by letting a second encoder pass allocate support on the first-pass reconstruction residual, reducing one-shot top-k competition without changing the execution layer."}}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:45:{"event_id": "evt_1773954033361528222", "ts": 1773954033, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 7, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "residual_topk", "family_stage": "stabilize", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "residual_topk", "family_stage": "stabilize", "change_type": "edit_sae_code", "expected_win": "lower_fvu", "hypothesis": "The current residual_topk prototype is likely capped by its fixed half-and-half latent budget: each branch can only nominate roughly K/2 features before the final merge, so the better branch cannot claim more of the final support even when it should. Letting both branches over-propose up to K candidates and then selecting the final global top-K from their union should preserve the residual design while removing this allocation bottleneck, improving FVU at fixed K=128."}}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:56:{"event_id": "evt_1773954198413164826", "ts": 1773954198, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 8, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "factorized_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "factorized_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "change_type": "edit_sae_code", "expected_win": "lower_fvu", "hypothesis": "At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated factorized_topk SAE with a narrow nonlinear hidden mixing stage will beat the current rotated linear top-k proxy anchor on FVU by giving the encoder more expressive support selection than a single linear projection, without changing the fixed-K decode path."}}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/timeline.jsonl:67:{"event_id": "evt_1773954346679443148", "ts": 1773954346, "event": "agent_action_received", "round": 9, "tier": "proxy", "run_name": null, "family_name": "mixture_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "status": null, "decision": null, "payload": {"tier": "proxy", "family_name": "mixture_topk", "family_stage": "prototype", "change_type": "edit_sae_code", "expected_win": "lower_fvu", "hypothesis": "At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated mixture_topk SAE with a softly routed two-expert encoder will lower proxy FVU versus the current linear top-k anchor by letting different encoder experts specialize to different token regimes without the hard capacity bottlenecks and optimization friction seen in grouped routing variants."}}
